            <div id="act2-explanation" class="hidden px-4 pb-4 grid gap-3">
              <p class="text-sm opacity-80 leading-relaxed"><span class="text-[#9b7ab8] font-mono">Bitwise operators (&amp;, ^, ~, ^=)</span> — These operate directly on the binary representation of integers. For example, <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">a &amp; c</span> compares each bit of 5 (0101) and 13 (1101), yielding 5 (0101). The NOT operator <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">~a</span> flips all bits, making it a large negative number and not equal to <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">a</span>.</p>
              <p class="text-sm opacity-80 leading-relaxed"><span class="text-[#9b7ab8] font-mono">Ternary operator (condition ? a : b)</span> — A shorthand for if-else that evaluates a condition and returns one of two values. Used here to compare two integers and return either <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">true/false</span> or the smaller/larger value.</p>
              <p class="text-sm opacity-80 leading-relaxed"><span class="text-[#9b7ab8] font-mono">Assignment operators (+=, -=, *=, /=)</span> — Shorthand operators that perform an arithmetic operation and assign the result back to the variable in one step. For example, <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">x += b</span> is equivalent to <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">x = x + b</span>.</p>
              <p class="text-sm opacity-80 leading-relaxed"><span class="text-[#9b7ab8] font-mono">Prefix vs. postfix (p++ + ++p)</span> — Postfix <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">p++</span> uses the current value first, then increments. Prefix <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">++p</span> increments first, then uses the new value. In <span class="text-[#b76cff] font-mono">p++ + ++p</span> with p=7, it evaluates as 7 + 9 = 16 since p becomes 8 before the prefix increment fires.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
